    <h1 class="tips-page__title">Tips &amp; Tricks</h1>
    <p class="tips-page__dek">Clinical pearls from the consult room  -  small things that work, passed on informally and rarely written down.</p>
  </header>

  <div class="tips-grid">

    <article class="tip-card">
      <p class="tip-tag">❍ Dermatology</p>
      <h2 class="tip-title">The burrow ink test for scabies</h2>
      <p class="tip-body">Apply ink broadly over the suspicious area  -  a fountain pen or felt-tip works  -  then wipe off the excess with an alcohol swab. Ink retained in burrow tracks reveals the characteristic linear or S-shaped burrow of <em>Sarcoptes scabiei</em> clearly against the skin. Useful when the rash is atypical or distribution is uncertain. Costs nothing, takes 30 seconds.</p>
      <p class="tip-footer">Dermatology · <a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.331.7517.619" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Johnston &amp; Sladden, BMJ 2005</a></p>
    </article>

    <article class="tip-card">
      <p class="tip-tag">❍ Gastroenterology</p>
      <h2 class="tip-title">Gladwrap across the toilet bowl for stool samples</h2>
      <p class="tip-body">Tell patients to stretch a piece of cling film across the toilet bowl before opening their bowels. The sample collects on the film rather than dispersing into the water, making collection clean and straightforward. Works for the specimen quality needed for calprotectin, <em>C. difficile</em> PCR, or culture. This is the step most labs forget to mention on the request form.</p>
      <p class="tip-footer">Gastroenterology · sample collection</p>
    </article>

    <article class="tip-card">
      <p class="tip-tag">❍ Rheumatology · Dermatology</p>
      <h2 class="tip-title">Nailfold capillaroscopy with a dermatoscope in Raynaud's phenomenon</h2>
      <p class="tip-body">Apply a drop of immersion oil to the nailfold of several fingers, then examine with a dermatoscope at maximum magnification (or an ophthalmoscope set to +40 dioptres). Normal capillary loops are orderly, uniform U-shapes in a row. The scleroderma pattern is dilated, distorted, or absent loops with haemorrhagic deposits. The distinction matters: primary Raynaud's has normal capillaries; secondary Raynaud's associated with systemic sclerosis, dermatomyositis, or mixed connective tissue disease does not. Takes 3-5 minutes. A single abnormal nailfold is enough to warrant rheumatology referral.</p>
      <p class="tip-footer">Rheumatology · dermatology · Smith V et al, Autoimmun Rev 2019;18(3):315–23</p>
    </article>

    <article class="tip-card">
      <p class="tip-tag">❍ Dermatology</p>
      <h2 class="tip-title">Nikolsky's sign for blistering disorders</h2>
      <p class="tip-body">Apply lateral shearing pressure with a finger to apparently normal skin adjacent to a blister. Epidermal separation = positive. Positive in pemphigus vulgaris, where blistering is intraepidermal and the skin is extremely fragile. Negative in bullous pemphigoid, where blistering is subepidermal and the skin holds. The distinction changes urgency immediately: pemphigus requires prompt systemic immunosuppression; pemphigoid is comparatively more indolent. A positive Nikolsky sign in a new blistering presentation warrants same-day or next-day dermatology contact.</p>
      <p class="tip-footer">Dermatology · blistering disorders · Nousari &amp; Anhalt, Lancet 1999;354(9179):667–72</p>
    </article>

  </div>

